## 1. Methodology: SBTDD + Document Hierarchy

This project follows the SBTDD paradigm
(Spec + Behavior + Test Driven Development).

### 1.1 Document hierarchy

| File | Purpose | Tracked |
|------|---------|---------|
| `~/.hermes/HERMES.md` | Global code rules — maximum precedence | Global, outside repo |
| `HERMES.md` | Developer-local permanent memory: lasting architecture decisions, accumulated context (NOT runtime state — see §2) | **No** — gitignored |
| `HERMES.local.md` | Project rules and standards (immutable during execution, see §2.4) | **No** — gitignored |
| `.hermes/` (entire directory) | Agent configuration: settings, state file, verification data | **No** — gitignored |
| `sbtdd/spec-behavior-base.md` | Base spec pre-brainstorming (input to brainstorming) | **No** — gitignored |
| `sbtdd/spec-behavior.md` | SDD + BDD specification of the active feature (output of brainstorming) | **No** — gitignored |
| `planning/hermes-plan-tdd.md` | Active TDD plan, reviewed and approved | **No** — gitignored |
| `planning/hermes-plan-tdd-org.md` | Original TDD plan generated by `/skill plan` (pre-MAGI reference) | **No** — gitignored |

**Tracking policy:**

`HERMES.md`, `HERMES.local.md`, `.hermes/`, `sbtdd/`, and `planning/` are all
**gitignored**. The entire SBTDD process is **developer-local**; git records
source code and TDD-cycle commits only. There is no shared team coordination
via these artifacts — each developer instantiates their own local configuration
from the template. If lasting architecture decisions need to be shared, commit
them to project documentation (README, docs/), not to `HERMES.md`.

### Spec workflow

Before writing a single line of code:

1. `sbtdd/spec-behavior-base.md` must be complete — objective, requirements (SDD),
   scenarios Given/When/Then (BDD), constraints, non-goals.
2. Generate `sbtdd/spec-behavior.md` from `spec-behavior-base.md` via manual
   brainstorming or `/skill plan`.
3. Run `/skill plan` using `sbtdd/spec-behavior.md` as context to generate
   `planning/hermes-plan-tdd-org.md`.
4. Manual review (Checkpoint 1) — if the user rejects, regenerate with feedback.
5. MAGI review (Checkpoint 2) — run `/skill magi` with spec + plan as context.
   Iterate until verdict ≥ `GO WITH CAVEATS`.
   **Safety valve:** after 3 iterations below threshold, stop and escalate —
   the spec likely has structural problems.
6. Final plan approval.

If any artifact is missing or incomplete, stop and request it.

